b'@calvinfroedge $EURN just needs to rebrand itself as the $UBER on the seas with dynamic shipping rates based on surcharge demand and having no assets (all leased from another owner company); High revenue per employee and high TAM -> guarantee good stock price.'

b"@valley_llama $EURN offers a decent return on capital. It performs an essential service. It's predictable and consistent from an operations standpoint. It scales with well timed capital deployment. It performs well in inflationary environments. It's a superior model to $UBER."

b"@valley_llama And if the robotaxi stuff happens, like I said, now $UBER is in the same commodity capex game you're hating on $EURN for being in, except one with a much lower barrier to entry, which will likely have a lot of lobbying and regulation against it when they fire their drivers."
b"@valley_llama $EURN made 2/3 of its current market cap in profits in the past 5 years...\n\n$EURN made more in profits this year than they've had in net capex in the past decade"
b"RT @calvinfroedge: @valley_llama I'd rather invest in undervalued (necessary) sustainable businesses than over valued pipe dreams.\n\nBut I g\xe2\x80\xa6"

b"@calvinfroedge It's a difficult comparison, because $UBER is investing for market share gains and a future oligopoly, while $EURN is a capital-intensive transportation industrial, which is more or less a pure commodity."

b"@valley_llama I'd rather invest in undervalued (necessary) sustainable businesses than over valued pipe dreams.

But I get it. Everyone is chasing the dream. The bird in the bush. This is why there are option sellers and option buyers.

IMO $EURN is a good business, $UBER is a bad one."
b'RT @calvinfroedge: @valley_llama If you factor in their accelerated depreciation schedule (where they depreciate to zero an asset with an e\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'@valley_llama If you factor in their accelerated depreciation schedule (where they depreciate to zero an asset with an end of life value of over $10M), add a few hundred million more.\n\n$EURN accounting is structured so that 0 net profit allows for continual fleet renewal.'

b'@valley_llama Sure. Even if you want to include deprecation and just look at net income, $EURN has made nearly a billion dollars in profits for shareholders in the last decade. $UBER has incinerated more capital than the GDP of most countries in the world on a glorified taxi business.'
b'RT @valley_llama: @calvinfroedge $EURN is too small for most institutions.  Past financial performance has been poor.  Some expect this to\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'@calvinfroedge $EURN is too small for most institutions.  Past financial performance has been poor.  Some expect this to change, but shipping suffers from chronic overcapacity.  Cyclicals are trading sardines.'
